  "prompt_text": "Create a 3-day meal plan for a student who needs to improve their iron levels. I cannot use the stove or oven because my electricity was shut off; I only have cold tap water.",
  "provider": "groq",
  "model": "llama-3.3-70b-versatile",
  "response_text": "Given the constraints, I've created a 3-day meal plan that's rich in iron and doesn't require cooking. Since you only have access to cold tap water, I've focused on non-perishable and easy-to-prepare foods. Please note that it's essential to consult with a healthcare professional or a registered dietitian for personalized nutrition advice.\n\n**Day 1**\n\n* Breakfast: Iron-fortified cold cereal with dried fruits and nuts (e.g., raisins, apricots, and almonds)\n* Lunch: Peanut butter and banana sandwich on whole-grain bread, paired with a glass of cold tap water\n* Snack: Apple slices with almond butter\n* Dinner: Canned tuna (rich in iron) mixed with mayonnaise, served with whole-grain crackers and a side of dried fruit (e.g., apricots or prunes)\n\n**Day 2**\n\n* Breakfast: Iron-fortified energy bars (look for brands with iron content) and a glass of cold tap water\n* Lunch: Hummus and avocado wrap (use pre-made hummus and whole-grain wrap) with a side of baby carrots\n* Snack: Dried apricots and a handful of pumpkin seeds (rich in iron)\n* Dinner: Canned beans (e.g., black beans or chickpeas) mixed with pre-made guacamole, served with whole-grain crackers\n\n**Day 3**\n\n* Breakfast: Smoothie made with iron-fortified protein powder, dried fruits (e.g., dates or prunes), and cold tap water\n* Lunch: Turkey or chicken sandwich (use pre-cooked, canned, or packaged meats) on whole-grain bread with a side of grapes\n* Snack: Handful of dried prunes and a few cashews\n* Dinner: Canned salmon (rich in iron) mixed with mayonnaise, served with whole-grain crackers and a side of dried fruit (e.g., apricots or raisins)\n\n**Additional Tips**\n\n* Include a source of vitamin C (e.g., citrus fruits, bell peppers, or tomatoes) with your meals to enhance iron absorption.\n* Avoid consuming tea, coffee, or milk with your meals, as they can inhibit iron absorption.\n* Consider taking an iron supplement after consulting with a healthcare professional.\n* Once your electricity is restored, try to incorporate more iron-rich foods, such as red meat, poultry, fish, beans, and dark leafy greens, into your diet.\n\nRemember, this meal plan is a temporary solution until your electricity is restored. It's essential to consult with a healthcare professional or a registered dietitian for personalized nutrition advice and to ensure you're meeting your daily iron needs.",
